\title{\textbf{Algorithmic Stress Monitoring Pipeline: A GPU-Accelerated Multi-Pillar Framework for Physiological Occupational Health Analytics}}
\author{Hemant Aggarwal\\Department of Information Technology\\Indian Institute of Information Technology Allahabad\\Prayagraj, Uttar Pradesh, India\\\texttt{iit2023015@iiita.ac.in}}
\date{}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Algorithmic management systems increasingly decide work pace, task assignment, interruption frequency, and performance thresholds. These decisions can produce physiological strain before workers formally report fatigue or attrition risk. This paper presents the Algorithmic Stress Monitoring Pipeline (ASMP), an end-to-end framework that harmonizes wearable streams into a common 1 Hz schema and evaluates stress through five analytical pillars: attention-based sequence modelling, temporal convolution, reconstruction-based regime detection, psychological signature clustering, and neural survival modelling. A sixth research-design layer links model outputs to occupational-health theory, adjusted causal estimands, intervention contrasts, threshold robustness, and managerial safeguards. The implementation is GPU-enabled through explicit CUDA device routing and writes reproducible result artifacts, tables, dashboards, and screenshots for paper reporting. Current generated outputs show that high-stress exposure is associated with lower HRV and higher HR after adjustment, while threshold reports translate model evidence into decision-support signals rather than punitive surveillance scores.
\end{abstract}

\textbf{Keywords:} algorithmic management, physiological stress, wearable sensing, LSTM, TCN, autoencoder, DeepSurv, causal validation, occupational health, GPU analytics

\section{Introduction}
Algorithmic work systems coordinate labour through dynamic scheduling, route optimization, queue assignment, and productivity scoring. These systems can improve throughput, but they may also compress recovery time and create persistent monitoring pressure. In occupational-health terms, the relevant risk is not only whether a worker is stressed at one instant, but whether repeated demand shocks prevent physiological recovery.

ASMP addresses this problem by treating stress monitoring as a linked measurement and research-design problem. The measurement layer learns temporal stress signals from EDA, HR, temperature, accelerometry, and HRV. The research-design layer asks whether the learned signals are interpretable, parsimonious, robust to threshold choice, and useful for managerial decisions that reduce strain. This separation is important because high predictive accuracy alone is not sufficient for workplace deployment.

The main contributions are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item A harmonized physiological data pipeline for WESAD, induced-stress Empatica data, MMASH, SWELL, and synthetic fallback validation.
    \item GPU-ready training and evaluation for AttentionLSTM, CircadianAttentionLSTM, StressTCN, StressAutoencoder, and DeepSurv modules.
    \item A research-design layer that reports theory constructs, sample-to-parameter ratios, adjusted high-stress effects, intervention contrasts, external validation checks, and managerial implications.
    \item Programmatic paper artifacts: evaluation CSV/JSON files, training curves, dashboards, and rendered result screenshots.
\end{itemize}

\section{Data Harmonization and GPU Execution}
All streams are mapped to seven canonical physiological features:
\[
\mathbf{x}_t = [EDA_t, HR_t, TEMP_t, ACC^x_t, ACC^y_t, ACC^z_t, HRV_t].
\]
Each observation also carries a unified stress index, dataset provenance, subject identifier, and intervention label when available. The harmonizer resamples streams to 1 Hz, applies subject-level normalization, and filters movement-heavy periods when physical exertion could confound psychological stress.

The training pipeline selects CUDA when available and can be forced with \texttt{ASMP\_DEVICE=cuda}. Environment variables control epochs, batch size, sequence length, stride, number of workers, dataset paths, subject subsets, and full-data sampling. This makes the same code usable for quick CPU smoke tests and full GPU runs.

