\section{Analytical Pillars}
\subsection{Pillar 1: Long-Term Dynamics}
The AttentionLSTM models stress as a sequence problem. It learns which time steps in a 60-second window are most informative for predicting the end-of-window stress index. The CircadianAttentionLSTM adds harmonic positional encoding and an imbalance head, allowing the model to represent repeated stress-recovery asymmetry.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\safeinclude[width=0.9\linewidth]{outputs/circadian_curve.png}
\caption{Circadian proxy output showing predicted stress, imbalance, and attention structure.}
\label{fig:circadian}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Pillar 2: Short-Term Reactions}
The StressTCN uses causal temporal convolutions to detect acute physiological reactions. Compared with recurrent networks, this architecture is efficient on GPUs because window operations are parallelizable. It is used for short-burst stress responses that may not require a full recurrent state representation.

\subsection{Pillar 3: Latent Regime Detection}
The StressAutoencoder reconstructs physiological windows and treats high reconstruction error as a latent regime shift. In the current generated threshold report, 2 out of 39 validation windows were flagged at the 95th percentile threshold, corresponding to a normal warning state in the subject-level report. The exact counts update automatically after the full GPU run.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\safeinclude[width=0.92\linewidth]{outputs/regime_timeline.png}
\caption{Autoencoder reconstruction error timeline with 95th percentile regime threshold.}
\label{fig:regime}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Pillar 4: Psychological Signature Clustering}
Attention-weighted physiological profiles are clustered into three interpretable signatures: cognitive overload, high agitation, and stable pacing. These clusters convert high-dimensional model outputs into managerially interpretable physiological patterns.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{subfigure}{0.48\linewidth}
\centering
\safeinclude[width=\linewidth]{outputs/signature_heatmap.png}
\caption{Signature heatmap}
\end{subfigure}
\begin{subfigure}{0.48\linewidth}
\centering
\safeinclude[width=\linewidth]{outputs/pressure_nodes.png}
\caption{Pressure-node embedding}
\end{subfigure}
\caption{Psychological signature outputs from attention-weighted physiological profiles.}
\label{fig:signatures}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Pillar 5: Attrition and Burnout Risk}
DeepSurv estimates a log-risk score from aggregated physiological covariates using the Cox partial likelihood. The output is compared with a Cox proportional-hazards baseline through the concordance index when sufficient event variation is available. In deployment, this score should be used only as a decision-support signal for redesigning work conditions, not as an individual disciplinary metric.

\section{Research Design and Causal Evidence}
ASMP embeds model results in a research-design layer. The layer maps physiological metrics to constructs from Job Demands-Resources theory, Demand-Control theory, Effort-Recovery theory, and labour-economics interpretations of turnover risk.

The generated research-design summary reports the following current adjusted estimates:
\begin{itemize}
    \item High stress exposure, defined as \(\texttt{stress\_index} \geq 0.60\), is associated with lower HRV: effect \(=-1.0339\), 95\% CI \([-1.1120,-0.9662]\).
    \item High stress exposure is associated with higher HR: effect \(=+1.2675\), 95\% CI \([+1.1991,+1.3216]\).
    \item The high-demand intervention contrast increases the stress index by \(+0.5905\), with 95\% CI \([+0.5773,+0.6036]\) in the current generated output.
\end{itemize}

These estimates should be interpreted as adjusted associations under explicit assumptions, not as unrestricted causal proof. They become stronger when external holdout validation and source intervention labels support the same direction.

