\section{Managerial and Ethical Interpretation}
The pipeline is designed for redesigning work, not ranking workers. A high-stress flag should trigger investigation of workload, break timing, interruption frequency, shift design, or autonomy constraints. ASMP therefore reports policy implications alongside metrics. Current generated recommendations emphasize non-punitive decision support, recovery breaks, interruption reduction, external validation before deployment, and preference for parsimonious models unless complex models add validated value.

The survival and threshold modules are especially sensitive. They can identify patterns consistent with elevated attrition risk, but they should not be used to deny work opportunities, intensify monitoring, or make employment decisions without independent validation, human review, and organizational safeguards.

\section{Limitations}
The present implementation can run on synthetic fallback data or real datasets. Synthetic fallback is useful for validating code paths but cannot establish field performance. Real-data results depend on dataset label quality, sensor missingness, class balance, and whether interventions approximate workplace demand. The causal estimands rely on conditional exchangeability after adjustment for physical movement, temperature, and dataset indicators; unobserved confounding remains possible. External validation across organizations is required before deployment.

\section{Conclusion}
ASMP provides a reproducible GPU-ready pipeline for physiological stress analytics under algorithmic management. It integrates sequence models, convolutional models, anomaly detection, clustering, survival analysis, and research-design reporting. The strongest contribution is not a single model score, but a complete evidence chain: harmonized data, reproducible training, transparent metrics, robustness checks, screenshots of generated outputs, and managerial safeguards that translate physiological signals into work-redesign decisions.

